WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.303 --> 00:00:03.136
(dramatic music)

2
00:00:08.070 --> 00:00:11.130
<v Host>Okay, Dr. Levine, it is all yours sir.</v>

3
00:00:11.130 --> 00:00:12.390
Please take it away.

4
00:00:12.390 --> 00:00:14.100
<v ->All right, I'm back.</v>

5
00:00:14.100 --> 00:00:17.490
And for those of you who survived AKI, you get a treat.

6
00:00:17.490 --> 00:00:19.563
You get to hear about CKD.

7
00:00:20.400 --> 00:00:22.110
And I've not made any investments

8
00:00:22.110 --> 00:00:24.090
over the past half an hour,

9
00:00:24.090 --> 00:00:26.880
so there are no new disclosures.

10
00:00:26.880 --> 00:00:29.490
We're gonna talk now about CKD.

11
00:00:29.490 --> 00:00:32.370
I hope everybody has some water

12
00:00:32.370 --> 00:00:34.170
or other liquid in front of you

13
00:00:34.170 --> 00:00:36.630
'cause this really is a very dry subject.

14
00:00:36.630 --> 00:00:37.713
I apologize.

15
00:00:38.580 --> 00:00:43.320
There are about 35 million adults in this country with CKD,

16
00:00:43.320 --> 00:00:45.930
over 500,000 on dialysis,

17
00:00:45.930 --> 00:00:50.490
with 130,000 new dialysis patients annually.

18
00:00:50.490 --> 00:00:53.730
The only good news here is that the incidence prevalence

19
00:00:53.730 --> 00:00:58.730
of CKD has been stable roughly the past 10 to 15 years.

20
00:00:59.490 --> 00:01:01.980
Patients with CKD are more likely

21
00:01:01.980 --> 00:01:04.650
to die from cardiovascular disease,

22
00:01:04.650 --> 00:01:06.810
more likely to have infections

23
00:01:06.810 --> 00:01:08.793
than those who obviously don't.

24
00:01:10.260 --> 00:01:12.450
What are the risk factors for CKD?

25
00:01:12.450 --> 00:01:15.450
I've listed them in the next two slides alphabetically,

26
00:01:15.450 --> 00:01:18.330
but you really need to remember two important ones,

27
00:01:18.330 --> 00:01:20.717
diabetes and hypertension,

28
00:01:20.717 --> 00:01:23.760
'cause that's where things really are.

29
00:01:23.760 --> 00:01:27.030
You can get CKD from Coronavirus.

30
00:01:27.030 --> 00:01:30.360
Many patients get AKI from that if they're sick enough

31
00:01:30.360 --> 00:01:32.043
to wind up in the ICU.

32
00:01:34.470 --> 00:01:39.470
Diabetic kidney disease accounts for 39% of CKD

33
00:01:39.900 --> 00:01:42.360
and the vast majority of that are Type 2,

34
00:01:42.360 --> 00:01:44.223
rather than Type 1 diabetics.

35
00:01:45.390 --> 00:01:48.060
For non-diabetic kidney disease, CKD,

36
00:01:48.060 --> 00:01:52.560
most of that is vascular and most of that is hypertension.

37
00:01:52.560 --> 00:01:57.343
Glomerular diseases which were minor contributors to AKI

38
00:01:58.860 --> 00:02:01.623
are much more major contributors to CKD.

39
00:02:02.880 --> 00:02:06.349
Whereas the tubular interstitial processes like ATN

40
00:02:06.349 --> 00:02:10.290
and AIN, which caused AKI are very unlikely

41
00:02:10.290 --> 00:02:12.693
to result in CKD.

42
00:02:13.860 --> 00:02:17.190
The ones that go on to dialysis and transplantation,

43
00:02:17.190 --> 00:02:21.210
the same big actors again: diabetes and hypertension.

44
00:02:21.210 --> 00:02:24.420
Anybody here see any patients with diabetes?

45
00:02:24.420 --> 00:02:26.820
Anybody see any patients with hypertension?

46
00:02:26.820 --> 00:02:29.970
So you got a great opportunity to work on these patients

47
00:02:29.970 --> 00:02:32.250
and prevent these things from happening.

48
00:02:32.250 --> 00:02:35.580
Chronic glomerulonephritis, polycystic kidney disease,

49
00:02:35.580 --> 00:02:39.250
chronic pyelo, chronic kidney stones can cause

50
00:02:40.200 --> 00:02:42.153
ESRD and transplant.

51
00:02:43.679 --> 00:02:47.490
Okay, here's our first question, pretty simple one.

52
00:02:47.490 --> 00:02:50.340
Stage four chronic kidney disease defined

53
00:02:50.340 --> 00:02:53.580
as an estimated GFR of what?

54
00:02:53.580 --> 00:02:55.990
60 to 90, 30 to 60,

55
00:02:55.990 --> 00:03:00.963
15 to 30, or less than 15 mLs per minute.

56
00:03:06.150 --> 00:03:07.950
And we did good on this one.

57
00:03:07.950 --> 00:03:10.680
Again, this is stage four

58
00:03:10.680 --> 00:03:13.893
is 15 to 30 mLs per minute.

59
00:03:14.850 --> 00:03:17.340
So what is the definition of CKD?

60
00:03:17.340 --> 00:03:21.570
Brought to you by the same people who defined AKI.

61
00:03:21.570 --> 00:03:26.570
It is A GFR of less than 60, with or without kidney damage,

62
00:03:28.230 --> 00:03:32.250
or the presence of kidney damage for more than three months.

63
00:03:32.250 --> 00:03:34.830
And that damage can be a nephrectomy.

64
00:03:34.830 --> 00:03:39.830
It could be a proteinuria that occurs.

65
00:03:40.170 --> 00:03:42.300
A proteinuria of significance

66
00:03:42.300 --> 00:03:46.863
with a relatively normal GFR is still gonna be CKD.

67
00:03:49.470 --> 00:03:53.460
We have five stages with some sub-stages in there.

68
00:03:53.460 --> 00:03:56.460
Stage one, GFR is fairly normal

69
00:03:56.460 --> 00:04:00.420
but there's evidence of kidney damage, like proteinuria.

70
00:04:00.420 --> 00:04:04.020
Stage two that GFR is between 60 and 90.

71
00:04:04.020 --> 00:04:08.080
Stage three, the GFR between 45 and 60

72
00:04:08.080 --> 00:04:09.747
is 3a, 3b, 30 to 45.

73
00:04:11.700 --> 00:04:14.310
And the reason we subdivide that is we're starting

74
00:04:14.310 --> 00:04:18.270
to see metabolic consequences when you hit stage 3b,

75
00:04:18.270 --> 00:04:20.220
so be aware of that.

76
00:04:20.220 --> 00:04:22.770
Stage four is when we start to dial in

77
00:04:22.770 --> 00:04:25.890
nephrologists generally, if we've not done so already.

78
00:04:25.890 --> 00:04:28.920
Stage five is where we actually treat that patient

79
00:04:28.920 --> 00:04:30.573
for end stage kidney disease.

80
00:04:32.910 --> 00:04:37.217
Albuminuria occurs in stages as well: A1, A2, and A3.

81
00:04:38.244 --> 00:04:43.244
A1 is normal, a microalbumin/creatine ratio less than 30.

82
00:04:43.500 --> 00:04:47.310
A2 is 30 to 300, which is microalbuminuria.

83
00:04:47.310 --> 00:04:50.160
Over 300, macroalbuminuria.

84
00:04:50.160 --> 00:04:52.563
Know those terms for the boards.

85
00:04:54.390 --> 00:04:57.870
Do we screen patients in practice for CKD?

86
00:04:57.870 --> 00:05:01.740
Well the U.S. Preventive Services Task Force said

87
00:05:01.740 --> 00:05:06.180
insufficient evidence to make a recommendation back in 2012.

88
00:05:07.500 --> 00:05:10.110
They made it inactive in 2016

89
00:05:10.110 --> 00:05:13.080
and they're currently reviewing it as we speak.

90
00:05:13.080 --> 00:05:15.840
So look for a recommendation from them again,

91
00:05:15.840 --> 00:05:17.313
sometime in the near future.

92
00:05:18.750 --> 00:05:20.550
If you have a patient with CKD,

93
00:05:20.550 --> 00:05:23.610
there's a certain evaluation you should do for them.

94
00:05:23.610 --> 00:05:27.780
You wanna assess their GFR, their protein excretion,

95
00:05:27.780 --> 00:05:29.610
and you may wanna do some blood work

96
00:05:29.610 --> 00:05:31.650
and some imaging as well.

97
00:05:31.650 --> 00:05:35.130
Kidney biopsies are indicated in certain instances

98
00:05:35.130 --> 00:05:37.440
and we'll discuss those a little bit later.

99
00:05:37.440 --> 00:05:40.500
So what are the things you're gonna do in your practice?

100
00:05:40.500 --> 00:05:41.333
You're gonna do a urine.

101
00:05:41.333 --> 00:05:44.730
You can look at a microscopic evaluation of that.

102
00:05:44.730 --> 00:05:49.680
You're gonna do a random or 24 hour creatinine estimation

103
00:05:49.680 --> 00:05:52.890
or clearance or one for protein as well.

104
00:05:52.890 --> 00:05:55.800
You're gonna check a CBC and a metabolic panel

105
00:05:55.800 --> 00:05:59.193
looking at calcium, phosphorus and uric acid.

106
00:06:00.390 --> 00:06:02.760
Wise to do a serum protein electrophoresis.

107
00:06:02.760 --> 00:06:05.523
You don't wanna miss CKD dual myelomas.

108
00:06:06.690 --> 00:06:10.923
Hepatitis B, hepatitis C, HIV,

109
00:06:11.850 --> 00:06:14.040
nephrologist will do those tests if you don't,

110
00:06:14.040 --> 00:06:18.000
because anybody heading to dialysis needs to know that.

111
00:06:18.000 --> 00:06:22.800
And there also are those viruses can cause CKD.

112
00:06:22.800 --> 00:06:25.440
An ANA complement studies, ANCA,

113
00:06:25.440 --> 00:06:29.070
anti-GBM antibody, those are more sophisticated

114
00:06:29.070 --> 00:06:30.513
that we don't always do.

115
00:06:32.040 --> 00:06:34.320
It's wise to image a patient

116
00:06:34.320 --> 00:06:35.910
whose creatinines are getting high

117
00:06:35.910 --> 00:06:37.170
and GFRs are getting low

118
00:06:37.170 --> 00:06:39.450
to make sure they don't have an obstruction,

119
00:06:39.450 --> 00:06:43.320
which is something fairly simple to correct.

120
00:06:43.320 --> 00:06:46.020
And a renal ultrasound carries no risk

121
00:06:46.020 --> 00:06:47.800
and is very good for that.

122
00:06:47.800 --> 00:06:51.510
CT scans, MRIs, renal angiograms,

123
00:06:51.510 --> 00:06:54.723
those are things that are for specific indications.

124
00:06:55.590 --> 00:06:57.360
What about our renal biopsies?

125
00:06:57.360 --> 00:06:59.850
If you have a patient with persistent hematuria,

126
00:06:59.850 --> 00:07:02.760
a low GFR, persistent proteinuria,

127
00:07:02.760 --> 00:07:04.950
particularly its nephrotic range,

128
00:07:04.950 --> 00:07:07.860
CKD is not known and they don't have

129
00:07:07.860 --> 00:07:12.663
big or large kidneys, then you can go ahead and biopsy them.

130
00:07:13.710 --> 00:07:15.600
I'm sorry, they have big or large,

131
00:07:15.600 --> 00:07:18.240
normal or big kidneys, they don't have small kidneys,

132
00:07:18.240 --> 00:07:19.240
you can biopsy them.

133
00:07:22.410 --> 00:07:24.390
Moving on to the next question.

134
00:07:24.390 --> 00:07:28.170
Nephrogenic systemic fibrosis may occur as a result

135
00:07:28.170 --> 00:07:30.240
of which of the following?

136
00:07:30.240 --> 00:07:33.210
Chemotherapy with an alkylating agent,

137
00:07:33.210 --> 00:07:36.690
hemodialysis, peritoneal dialysis,

138
00:07:36.690 --> 00:07:39.483
or MRI with gadolinium contrast.

139
00:07:44.700 --> 00:07:48.123
And you voted for MRI with gadolinium and that's correct.

140
00:07:49.110 --> 00:07:51.213
How many of you have seen a case of this?

141
00:07:52.470 --> 00:07:55.380
How many of you have heard of a case of this?

142
00:07:55.380 --> 00:07:56.223
Very good.

143
00:07:58.500 --> 00:08:01.080
This is a condition that occurs

144
00:08:01.080 --> 00:08:02.700
or has occurred in stage four

145
00:08:02.700 --> 00:08:05.640
to five chronic kidney disease patients,

146
00:08:05.640 --> 00:08:09.990
particularly on dialysis who are given an MRI

147
00:08:09.990 --> 00:08:13.470
with an older gadolinium-based contrast agent.

148
00:08:13.470 --> 00:08:15.870
And gadolinium is a cation.

149
00:08:15.870 --> 00:08:18.180
It complexes with various anions

150
00:08:18.180 --> 00:08:21.780
and causes insoluble precipitates in tissues

151
00:08:21.780 --> 00:08:24.150
that you don't want those in.

152
00:08:24.150 --> 00:08:26.400
Also fibrosis then occurs,

153
00:08:26.400 --> 00:08:28.770
skin plaques, joint contractures,

154
00:08:28.770 --> 00:08:31.470
and fibrosis in vital organs.

155
00:08:31.470 --> 00:08:33.420
Problem with this is if it occurs,

156
00:08:33.420 --> 00:08:35.550
there's really no way to really treat this,

157
00:08:35.550 --> 00:08:37.500
so you wanna not let it happen.

158
00:08:37.500 --> 00:08:41.010
Happens post-op with infections, thrombosis

159
00:08:41.010 --> 00:08:42.393
or in patients on EPO.

160
00:08:43.920 --> 00:08:45.840
So we recommended for a while

161
00:08:45.840 --> 00:08:50.400
that you not use gadolinium contrast in patients CKD four,

162
00:08:50.400 --> 00:08:52.023
particularly CKD five.

163
00:08:54.900 --> 00:08:58.470
Now we've also learned that recently the last five,

164
00:08:58.470 --> 00:09:01.200
10 years, we've not seen many cases of this.

165
00:09:01.200 --> 00:09:04.290
So with the newer agents it's probably not

166
00:09:04.290 --> 00:09:06.570
as bad a problem like it was in the past.

167
00:09:06.570 --> 00:09:10.620
But the board had a question on this and its SAMS

168
00:09:10.620 --> 00:09:14.880
and knowledge based things they had before,

169
00:09:14.880 --> 00:09:18.153
so beware that they may potentially ask something like that.

170
00:09:19.710 --> 00:09:22.053
How do you manage chronic kidney disease?

171
00:09:22.950 --> 00:09:25.350
Specific therapy, based on the diagnosis.

172
00:09:25.350 --> 00:09:29.010
You wanna do things to slow the loss of kidney function.

173
00:09:29.010 --> 00:09:31.620
You wanna identify and treat comorbid conditions,

174
00:09:31.620 --> 00:09:33.633
particularly involving the heart.

175
00:09:34.830 --> 00:09:38.490
You wanna prepare the patient for potentially

176
00:09:38.490 --> 00:09:39.510
needing a transplant

177
00:09:39.510 --> 00:09:41.970
or dialysis if they continue to get worse.

178
00:09:41.970 --> 00:09:44.129
Treat complications that arise related

179
00:09:44.129 --> 00:09:46.113
to their chronic kidney disorder.

180
00:09:47.490 --> 00:09:49.590
And our management changes by the stage

181
00:09:49.590 --> 00:09:51.270
of chronic kidney disease.

182
00:09:51.270 --> 00:09:53.940
Early on, again, we're trying to treat things

183
00:09:53.940 --> 00:09:55.260
that are going on

184
00:09:55.260 --> 00:09:58.080
and identifying any premorbid conditions.

185
00:09:58.080 --> 00:10:01.800
Stage three particularly b, we're treating complications.

186
00:10:01.800 --> 00:10:04.920
Stage four, we're talking with that nephrologist,

187
00:10:04.920 --> 00:10:06.660
preparing the patient that they may,

188
00:10:06.660 --> 00:10:09.660
if they get worse, need dialysis or transplant,

189
00:10:09.660 --> 00:10:11.613
which happens with stage five.

190
00:10:12.750 --> 00:10:16.020
Patients have a role in this as well.

191
00:10:16.020 --> 00:10:17.460
Certainly if they're diabetic,

192
00:10:17.460 --> 00:10:19.350
they need to maintain their sugars.

193
00:10:19.350 --> 00:10:22.710
Hypertension, watch their pressures and control their diet

194
00:10:22.710 --> 00:10:25.800
and take their meds, get rid of those cigarettes,

195
00:10:25.800 --> 00:10:28.260
exercise and take the medications

196
00:10:28.260 --> 00:10:31.650
that we appropriately prescribe for them.

197
00:10:31.650 --> 00:10:35.970
Monitor their GFR creatinine clearance at least yearly,

198
00:10:35.970 --> 00:10:39.270
more often if those creatinines are rising

199
00:10:39.270 --> 00:10:42.780
or if they're getting worse for one reason or another.

200
00:10:42.780 --> 00:10:45.990
Always review medications with your renal patients.

201
00:10:45.990 --> 00:10:47.700
We do that with everybody anyway,

202
00:10:47.700 --> 00:10:50.820
but really with these patients it's extremely important

203
00:10:50.820 --> 00:10:54.660
because as kidney function changes, medication doses change,

204
00:10:54.660 --> 00:10:57.120
certain things become contraindicated

205
00:10:57.120 --> 00:10:59.580
and you want to make sure your patient's getting

206
00:10:59.580 --> 00:11:00.780
the appropriate therapy.

207
00:11:02.130 --> 00:11:05.130
There are a number of things that are associated with CKD.

208
00:11:05.130 --> 00:11:08.850
We're gonna talk about them for the rest of this session,

209
00:11:08.850 --> 00:11:13.650
things like hypertension, anemia, acidosis, hyperkalemia,

210
00:11:13.650 --> 00:11:17.013
bone disorders, and some cardiovascular issues as well.

211
00:11:19.920 --> 00:11:21.370
So here's your next question.

212
00:11:22.500 --> 00:11:23.700
Which of the following statements

213
00:11:23.700 --> 00:11:26.973
are true about CKD and hypertension?

214
00:11:28.230 --> 00:11:29.457
Most patients with hypertension

215
00:11:29.457 --> 00:11:33.180
and elevated creatinine levels can be treated safely

216
00:11:33.180 --> 00:11:35.253
with an ACE inhibitor or an ARB.

217
00:11:36.540 --> 00:11:41.043
JNC-8 recommends a target blood pressure of 130/90.

218
00:11:42.060 --> 00:11:47.060
ACC/AHA recommends a target blood pressure of 140/90

219
00:11:48.420 --> 00:11:52.113
in patients who have an albumin/creatinine ratio over 300.

220
00:11:53.610 --> 00:11:55.680
Hypertension in patient with CKD

221
00:11:55.680 --> 00:11:58.863
is typically not responsive to diuretic therapy.

222
00:12:04.146 --> 00:12:07.500
And you voted for the top one, which is correct.

223
00:12:07.500 --> 00:12:09.030
Most patients with hypertension,

224
00:12:09.030 --> 00:12:11.940
elevated creatinines can be treated safely

225
00:12:11.940 --> 00:12:14.163
with an ACE inhibitor or an ARB.

226
00:12:15.600 --> 00:12:18.450
JNC-8 came out in 2014.

227
00:12:18.450 --> 00:12:22.293
The lead author was a family physician, University of Iowa.

228
00:12:23.370 --> 00:12:27.813
In general population, our target was 150/90.

229
00:12:29.430 --> 00:12:31.650
Those younger, 140/90,

230
00:12:31.650 --> 00:12:34.320
so higher range blood pressures.

231
00:12:34.320 --> 00:12:37.287
But those with diabetes or CKD,

232
00:12:37.287 --> 00:12:41.580
the number was 140/90, like those who were younger.

233
00:12:41.580 --> 00:12:43.920
And that was JNC-8.

234
00:12:43.920 --> 00:12:47.040
They recommended we treat CKD patients

235
00:12:47.040 --> 00:12:48.513
with an ACE or an ARB.

236
00:12:49.890 --> 00:12:52.950
If they didn't have CKD but had hypertension,

237
00:12:52.950 --> 00:12:54.570
then first line agents,

238
00:12:54.570 --> 00:12:57.720
African American patients, thiazide diuretic

239
00:12:57.720 --> 00:12:59.610
or a calcium channel blocker.

240
00:12:59.610 --> 00:13:02.460
Caucasian patients, either of those two

241
00:13:02.460 --> 00:13:04.530
or an ACE or an ARB.

242
00:13:04.530 --> 00:13:05.793
So that is JNC-8.

243
00:13:07.500 --> 00:13:10.200
The ACC, American College of Cardiology,

244
00:13:10.200 --> 00:13:11.550
American Heart Association,

245
00:13:11.550 --> 00:13:13.770
their guidelines came out later.

246
00:13:13.770 --> 00:13:17.430
They're based on the SPRINT study that was done.

247
00:13:17.430 --> 00:13:19.116
They looked at normal blood pressures

248
00:13:19.116 --> 00:13:22.800
at a lower range than JNC-8,

249
00:13:22.800 --> 00:13:26.490
where stage two hypertension was 140/90,

250
00:13:26.490 --> 00:13:29.043
normal less than 120/80.

251
00:13:30.150 --> 00:13:34.830
They recommended a target of 140/90

252
00:13:34.830 --> 00:13:38.100
in patients with no cardiovascular disease

253
00:13:38.100 --> 00:13:40.350
and a low 10 year risk.

254
00:13:40.350 --> 00:13:44.753
If they had cardiovascular disease, a risk of over 10%,

255
00:13:45.870 --> 00:13:48.447
then it was 130/80.

256
00:13:48.447 --> 00:13:51.690
In the elderly it was 130 systolic.

257
00:13:51.690 --> 00:13:55.770
Same thing with diabetes, same thing with CKD

258
00:13:55.770 --> 00:13:58.440
130/80 for most people,

259
00:13:58.440 --> 00:14:00.540
again based on the SPRINT study,

260
00:14:00.540 --> 00:14:02.340
which said the lower the blood pressure,

261
00:14:02.340 --> 00:14:04.113
the better that they tended to do.

262
00:14:05.520 --> 00:14:08.370
So their recommendations about therapy.

263
00:14:08.370 --> 00:14:12.903
CKD with macroalbuminuria, an ACE or an ARB.

264
00:14:14.190 --> 00:14:17.670
CKD without macroalbuminuria you could use any

265
00:14:17.670 --> 00:14:21.420
of the usual blood pressure medicines, diuretics,

266
00:14:21.420 --> 00:14:24.420
CCBs, ACEs or ARBs.

267
00:14:24.420 --> 00:14:28.230
So that came from ACC/AHA.

268
00:14:28.230 --> 00:14:29.610
Then they're the kidney folks.

269
00:14:29.610 --> 00:14:31.560
They have their own recommendations,

270
00:14:31.560 --> 00:14:35.550
but they support most of what came out of the ACC

271
00:14:35.550 --> 00:14:37.650
and the AHA.

272
00:14:37.650 --> 00:14:40.150
They said prescribe ACE or ARB

273
00:14:41.010 --> 00:14:43.200
in chronic kidney disease with hypertension

274
00:14:43.200 --> 00:14:46.890
if the patient has diabetes or proteinuria.

275
00:14:46.890 --> 00:14:50.010
Diuretics used in most patients

276
00:14:50.010 --> 00:14:53.670
and other regimens as needed by other conditions

277
00:14:53.670 --> 00:14:55.353
that they may in fact have.

278
00:14:56.760 --> 00:14:59.190
So ACE and ARBs can be used safely

279
00:14:59.190 --> 00:15:00.517
in most patients with CKD.

280
00:15:01.770 --> 00:15:03.810
When ACEs first came out,

281
00:15:03.810 --> 00:15:06.060
nephrologists said don't use 'em in patients

282
00:15:06.060 --> 00:15:07.760
with a creatinine more than three.

283
00:15:08.640 --> 00:15:10.680
Then it was more than five.

284
00:15:10.680 --> 00:15:12.450
Then it was more than eight.

285
00:15:12.450 --> 00:15:14.190
And then they got rid of it all together.

286
00:15:14.190 --> 00:15:15.780
So there's no creatinine

287
00:15:15.780 --> 00:15:20.313
or GFR mechanism for not using ACEs or ARBs.

288
00:15:21.600 --> 00:15:24.930
Continue them unless these GFR declines

289
00:15:24.930 --> 00:15:27.390
are more than 30% from baseline.

290
00:15:27.390 --> 00:15:29.430
We talked about that earlier.

291
00:15:29.430 --> 00:15:32.420
Also, stop 'em if potassium is more than 5.5.

292
00:15:34.110 --> 00:15:36.120
Usually a moderate to high dose,

293
00:15:36.120 --> 00:15:39.210
just don't skimp on them if you're gonna use 'em.

294
00:15:39.210 --> 00:15:42.480
You can use an ACE or an ARB, your choice,

295
00:15:42.480 --> 00:15:44.640
but don't use them together.

296
00:15:44.640 --> 00:15:47.283
If use 'em together, patients don't do well.

297
00:15:48.870 --> 00:15:50.790
Most patients with CKD

298
00:15:50.790 --> 00:15:54.090
and hypertension should be on a diuretic.

299
00:15:54.090 --> 00:15:57.930
If that GFR is over 30, your thiazides work better

300
00:15:57.930 --> 00:16:00.030
for hypertension control.

301
00:16:00.030 --> 00:16:03.630
If it's less than 30, they don't work at all or work well.

302
00:16:03.630 --> 00:16:06.390
In those patients you wanna use a loop diuretic

303
00:16:06.390 --> 00:16:08.243
like furosemide or Bumex.

304
00:16:09.360 --> 00:16:12.780
Also, if you have patients who are quite volume expanded,

305
00:16:12.780 --> 00:16:17.100
you can use a loop diuretic and a thiazide diuretic together

306
00:16:17.100 --> 00:16:21.123
or metolazone that helps to decrease that edema.

307
00:16:22.020 --> 00:16:24.480
Be careful about potassium sparing diuretics

308
00:16:24.480 --> 00:16:26.580
in patients with low GFRs.

309
00:16:26.580 --> 00:16:28.860
Be careful about using them in combination

310
00:16:28.860 --> 00:16:32.403
with ACEs or ARBs because of hyperkalemia.

311
00:16:34.170 --> 00:16:37.230
We also recommend a dietary sodium intake

312
00:16:37.230 --> 00:16:39.180
of less than two grams

313
00:16:39.180 --> 00:16:41.970
in most patients with CKD and hypertension.

314
00:16:41.970 --> 00:16:45.000
Good luck in getting your patients to adhere to that.

315
00:16:45.000 --> 00:16:46.503
That's pretty darn difficult.

316
00:16:47.370 --> 00:16:50.100
So what do you do about these dueling guidelines?

317
00:16:50.100 --> 00:16:52.110
You know, you're gonna take a board exam.

318
00:16:52.110 --> 00:16:53.670
Which ones do you follow?

319
00:16:53.670 --> 00:16:56.760
Which ones do you follow in clinical practice?

320
00:16:56.760 --> 00:17:00.780
Well, we used to say follow JNC-8 for the boards,

321
00:17:00.780 --> 00:17:02.670
but the last run through the boards,

322
00:17:02.670 --> 00:17:04.830
we got feedback that they're also asking

323
00:17:04.830 --> 00:17:08.280
some questions related to ACC/AHA.

324
00:17:08.280 --> 00:17:10.140
So you might wanna know both.

325
00:17:10.140 --> 00:17:11.970
Dr. Fernhaber may cover more of

326
00:17:11.970 --> 00:17:15.180
that later in his cardiovascular agents.

327
00:17:15.180 --> 00:17:16.800
But usually if the board asks you

328
00:17:16.800 --> 00:17:19.140
about a specific recommendation,

329
00:17:19.140 --> 00:17:21.060
they'll tell you which specific guideline

330
00:17:21.060 --> 00:17:22.500
that they're referring to.

331
00:17:22.500 --> 00:17:23.970
They're not gonna ask you to try to guess

332
00:17:23.970 --> 00:17:27.153
what they're asking about and which guideline they're using.

333
00:17:28.320 --> 00:17:30.750
In general, in clinical practice,

334
00:17:30.750 --> 00:17:32.790
patient with the proteinuria should be treated

335
00:17:32.790 --> 00:17:34.840
more aggressively for their hypertension.

336
00:17:36.750 --> 00:17:40.320
Lower blood pressures usually give you better outcomes

337
00:17:40.320 --> 00:17:42.180
as long as the patient can tolerate it

338
00:17:42.180 --> 00:17:45.390
and doesn't get symptomatic hypotension.

339
00:17:45.390 --> 00:17:48.810
And again, ACEs or ARB plus a diuretic

340
00:17:48.810 --> 00:17:52.440
are the cornerstones pretty much of treating hypertension

341
00:17:52.440 --> 00:17:53.943
in patients with CKD.

342
00:17:57.780 --> 00:18:00.450
Moving on to talk about anemia.

343
00:18:00.450 --> 00:18:04.530
Which of the following is true regarding anemia and CKD?

344
00:18:04.530 --> 00:18:06.090
Packed red cell transfusion

345
00:18:06.090 --> 00:18:08.373
indicated for hemoglobin less than 10.

346
00:18:09.210 --> 00:18:12.540
A target hemoglobin for patients with CKD-4

347
00:18:12.540 --> 00:18:16.743
receiving EPO is 13 for women, 14 for men.

348
00:18:17.640 --> 00:18:21.453
Most anemia in patients with CKD is due to iron deficiency.

349
00:18:22.440 --> 00:18:26.790
Therapy with EPO is associated with an increased risk

350
00:18:26.790 --> 00:18:30.063
of MIs and thromboembolic events.

351
00:18:35.880 --> 00:18:37.290
You voted for the last one.

352
00:18:37.290 --> 00:18:40.383
Last one is correct, is correct.

353
00:18:41.880 --> 00:18:45.153
What about anemia in chronic kidney disease?

354
00:18:46.170 --> 00:18:47.505
The kidney folks recommend

355
00:18:47.505 --> 00:18:50.313
that you test for hemoglobin annually.

356
00:18:51.330 --> 00:18:53.680
Their diagnosed anemia is less than 13.5 in men

357
00:18:55.101 --> 00:18:56.523
and 12 in women.

358
00:18:58.320 --> 00:19:03.000
Also get a CBC looking at other blood factors.

359
00:19:03.000 --> 00:19:04.260
Get a ferritin.

360
00:19:04.260 --> 00:19:05.913
Get an iron saturation.

361
00:19:08.040 --> 00:19:10.800
Most anemia in chronic kidney disease

362
00:19:10.800 --> 00:19:14.190
turns out to be anemia of chronic disease.

363
00:19:14.190 --> 00:19:18.450
Those folks have low serum irons, low TIBCs,

364
00:19:18.450 --> 00:19:21.573
normal saturations and a normal ferritin,

365
00:19:22.446 --> 00:19:25.920
where opposed, those people with iron deficiency

366
00:19:25.920 --> 00:19:27.450
tend to have low irons,

367
00:19:27.450 --> 00:19:32.450
high TIBCs, low saturations,

368
00:19:32.460 --> 00:19:33.873
and a low ferritin.

369
00:19:34.830 --> 00:19:37.383
Most, again are anemia of chronic disease.

370
00:19:38.460 --> 00:19:40.650
Chronic kidney disease, the most common reason

371
00:19:40.650 --> 00:19:43.320
for anemia of chronic disease these days,

372
00:19:43.320 --> 00:19:46.593
but infections, malignancies can also do it.

373
00:19:47.868 --> 00:19:50.070
So how do you treat anemia of chronic disease?

374
00:19:50.070 --> 00:19:53.666
You treat the underlying cause if you identify it.

375
00:19:53.666 --> 00:19:56.250
If they don't get better and they're symptomatic,

376
00:19:56.250 --> 00:19:59.253
you can use an EPO stimulating agent,

377
00:20:00.120 --> 00:20:02.971
transfusions for those patients who don't do better

378
00:20:02.971 --> 00:20:05.730
by treating their underlying disease with EPO

379
00:20:05.730 --> 00:20:07.173
and are still symptomatic.

380
00:20:08.400 --> 00:20:10.050
So what is EPO?

381
00:20:10.050 --> 00:20:14.070
It's a glycoprotein produced in the kidney

382
00:20:14.070 --> 00:20:18.030
in response to decreased oxygen delivery to that kidney

383
00:20:18.030 --> 00:20:20.760
from anemia or hypoxemia.

384
00:20:20.760 --> 00:20:23.760
There are several of them on the market that we use,

385
00:20:23.760 --> 00:20:25.800
predominantly used in our community

386
00:20:25.800 --> 00:20:28.950
by the nephrologists and the hematologist.

387
00:20:28.950 --> 00:20:32.280
But in your community you may be the person giving EPO.

388
00:20:32.280 --> 00:20:36.630
But EPO only works if the iron is adequate.

389
00:20:36.630 --> 00:20:39.653
So you wanna maintain a ferritin of over 100

390
00:20:39.653 --> 00:20:42.300
and you may need to give iron to do so

391
00:20:42.300 --> 00:20:43.803
in addition to giving EPO.

392
00:20:44.670 --> 00:20:49.440
Consider them in CKD patients when the hemoglobin is 11

393
00:20:49.440 --> 00:20:51.900
or less than 10 if they're on dialysis,

394
00:20:51.900 --> 00:20:53.880
especially if they're symptomatic.

395
00:20:53.880 --> 00:20:56.760
But it can increase mortality,

396
00:20:56.760 --> 00:21:00.150
can cause MIs, can cause strokes,

397
00:21:00.150 --> 00:21:03.210
can cause tumor progression in cancer patients,

398
00:21:03.210 --> 00:21:05.910
and emboli in post-op patients as well.

399
00:21:05.910 --> 00:21:08.643
And don't use it in uncontrolled hypertension.

400
00:21:10.320 --> 00:21:12.810
Red cell transfusions, be careful about that

401
00:21:12.810 --> 00:21:14.340
in kidney patients.

402
00:21:14.340 --> 00:21:16.740
It may sensitize some different antigens

403
00:21:16.740 --> 00:21:19.740
and make them harder to get a kidney in the future.

404
00:21:19.740 --> 00:21:22.260
So don't do it willy-nilly.

405
00:21:22.260 --> 00:21:23.760
The target hemoglobin

406
00:21:23.760 --> 00:21:27.420
for EPO therapy in your renal patients is 11,

407
00:21:27.420 --> 00:21:29.313
but that's not a transfusion trigger.

408
00:21:30.210 --> 00:21:33.720
The most common acid base abnormality in CKD

409
00:21:33.720 --> 00:21:35.580
is which of the following?

410
00:21:35.580 --> 00:21:39.330
Metabolic acidosis, metabolic alkalosis,

411
00:21:39.330 --> 00:21:42.663
respiratory acidosis, or respiratory alkalosis.

412
00:21:48.030 --> 00:21:51.080
You got this one right, metabolic acidosis.

413
00:21:51.080 --> 00:21:53.370
Do you remember MUDPILES

414
00:21:53.370 --> 00:21:56.280
from back when you were a student or a resident?

415
00:21:56.280 --> 00:22:00.963
Well the U in MUDPILES stood for uremia, which is CKD.

416
00:22:01.800 --> 00:22:04.950
Diabetic ketoacidosis, alcoholic ketoacidosis,

417
00:22:04.950 --> 00:22:07.980
lactic acidosis, polyethylene,

418
00:22:07.980 --> 00:22:10.486
ethylene glycol ingestion, salicylates,

419
00:22:10.486 --> 00:22:14.853
all cause an increased anion gap metabolic acidosis.

420
00:22:16.200 --> 00:22:18.600
In the case of our kidney patients,

421
00:22:18.600 --> 00:22:21.753
it's due to decreased hydrogen ion excretion.

422
00:22:23.010 --> 00:22:24.930
A bicarb of less than 22

423
00:22:24.930 --> 00:22:28.410
is associated with an increased progression of CKD

424
00:22:28.410 --> 00:22:31.440
and increased overall mortality.

425
00:22:31.440 --> 00:22:36.158
So in CKD 3, 4, and 5, maintain that CO2,

426
00:22:36.158 --> 00:22:39.600
that bicarb on your basic metabolic panel

427
00:22:39.600 --> 00:22:42.630
over 22 if you can.

428
00:22:42.630 --> 00:22:44.490
And how are you gonna do that?

429
00:22:44.490 --> 00:22:47.220
You can give 'em bicarb tablets.

430
00:22:47.220 --> 00:22:48.870
You can give 'em sodium citrate,

431
00:22:48.870 --> 00:22:53.070
which is Shohl's solution metabolized onto bicarb

432
00:22:53.070 --> 00:22:56.913
or calcium citrate, acetate, or carbonate such as Tums.

433
00:22:59.070 --> 00:22:59.940
Next question.

434
00:22:59.940 --> 00:23:01.500
Which of the following patterns

435
00:23:01.500 --> 00:23:05.700
is commonly found in patients with CKD?

436
00:23:05.700 --> 00:23:10.230
Is it a high calcium, low phosphorus, high PTH?

437
00:23:10.230 --> 00:23:14.220
Low calcium, high phosphate, high PTH?

438
00:23:14.220 --> 00:23:18.030
High calcium, high phosphate, low PTH?

439
00:23:18.030 --> 00:23:22.605
Low calcium, high phosphorus or low PTH?

440
00:23:22.605 --> 00:23:25.522
(audience laughs)

441
00:23:27.240 --> 00:23:30.810
And you voted for B low calcium, high phosphorus,

442
00:23:30.810 --> 00:23:32.883
high PTH and that's correct.

443
00:23:33.990 --> 00:23:38.730
Now we're talking about mineral bone disorders, CKD-MBD.

444
00:23:38.730 --> 00:23:41.763
Used to say renal osteodystrophy.

445
00:23:43.710 --> 00:23:46.350
MBD is characterized by abnormalities

446
00:23:46.350 --> 00:23:50.723
of calcium phosphate and PTH, ectopic calcifications,

447
00:23:52.980 --> 00:23:55.233
abnormal mineralizations of the bones,

448
00:23:56.640 --> 00:23:57.873
lots of problems.

449
00:23:59.430 --> 00:24:03.330
The pattern you see is secondary hyperparathyroidism.

450
00:24:03.330 --> 00:24:06.690
Again the low calcium, high phosphate, and high PTH.

451
00:24:06.690 --> 00:24:09.900
The problem is that when the GFR decreases,

452
00:24:09.900 --> 00:24:14.760
phosphorus excretion decreases and phosphate levels go up.

453
00:24:14.760 --> 00:24:18.330
That then complexes with calcium that goes down.

454
00:24:18.330 --> 00:24:19.890
Then you need to get more calcium,

455
00:24:19.890 --> 00:24:24.240
but kidneys are diseased, don't make enough vitamin D

456
00:24:24.240 --> 00:24:26.040
and then the parathyroid kicks in

457
00:24:26.040 --> 00:24:27.930
and says we need more of all this stuff.

458
00:24:27.930 --> 00:24:31.353
So the PTH level goes up and that's the problem.

459
00:24:32.220 --> 00:24:33.270
So what do you do here?

460
00:24:33.270 --> 00:24:34.980
You measure calcium phosphate

461
00:24:34.980 --> 00:24:39.270
and PTH in patients with CKD-3 or worse.

462
00:24:39.270 --> 00:24:40.896
You try to treat that phosphate,

463
00:24:40.896 --> 00:24:42.930
get it toward a normal range.

464
00:24:42.930 --> 00:24:44.490
How do you do that?

465
00:24:44.490 --> 00:24:47.550
With dietary phosphate restrictions?

466
00:24:47.550 --> 00:24:49.680
If that doesn't work, restricting 800

467
00:24:49.680 --> 00:24:52.110
to 1,000 milligrams a day,

468
00:24:52.110 --> 00:24:54.713
then use a phosphate binder, okay.

469
00:24:55.650 --> 00:24:58.950
Remember Coca-Cola is phosphoric acid,

470
00:24:58.950 --> 00:25:01.250
so don't drink Coke if you have renal disease.

471
00:25:02.100 --> 00:25:05.190
What are the things we use to treat this, our binders?

472
00:25:05.190 --> 00:25:09.570
First line agents are the non-calcium containing binders.

473
00:25:09.570 --> 00:25:12.060
This is new over the last couple years.

474
00:25:12.060 --> 00:25:14.523
Things like sevelamer and lanthanum.

475
00:25:16.980 --> 00:25:20.790
The calcium containing binders were cheaper.

476
00:25:20.790 --> 00:25:23.700
Things like calcium carbonate, calcium acetate,

477
00:25:23.700 --> 00:25:26.250
but those are no longer first line agents.

478
00:25:26.250 --> 00:25:30.270
Stay away from antagel, aluminum hydroxide

479
00:25:30.270 --> 00:25:33.243
because you can get aluminum toxicity in kidney patients.

480
00:25:34.470 --> 00:25:36.060
What about DEXA scanning?

481
00:25:36.060 --> 00:25:37.650
You can use DEXA scanning.

482
00:25:37.650 --> 00:25:41.700
Had nothing to do with these MBD illness whatsoever.

483
00:25:41.700 --> 00:25:43.590
You can do it in renal patients.

484
00:25:43.590 --> 00:25:46.137
Bone X-rays are not indicated in patients

485
00:25:46.137 --> 00:25:48.243
who have high PTH levels.

486
00:25:49.620 --> 00:25:52.620
There's a entity called calciphylaxis.

487
00:25:52.620 --> 00:25:55.380
Have any you seen patients with this?

488
00:25:55.380 --> 00:25:57.000
It's no fun.

489
00:25:57.000 --> 00:25:59.040
You tend to see it in dialysis patients.

490
00:25:59.040 --> 00:26:00.480
They have calcium deposits

491
00:26:00.480 --> 00:26:02.940
in small vessels and they ulcerate.

492
00:26:02.940 --> 00:26:06.150
They have pretty unrelenting pain.

493
00:26:06.150 --> 00:26:08.130
The treatment is sodium thiosulfate,

494
00:26:08.130 --> 00:26:10.230
but doesn't work all that great.

495
00:26:10.230 --> 00:26:13.953
These patients typically have a fairly poor prognosis.

496
00:26:15.420 --> 00:26:17.700
Diabetic kidney disease occurs

497
00:26:17.700 --> 00:26:19.980
in about 20 to 40% of diabetics.

498
00:26:19.980 --> 00:26:21.120
It's the leading cause

499
00:26:21.120 --> 00:26:25.740
of end stage renal disease, dialysis, transplantation.

500
00:26:25.740 --> 00:26:28.770
Microalbuminuria is a marker for this.

501
00:26:28.770 --> 00:26:31.320
That's why we follow it closely.

502
00:26:31.320 --> 00:26:35.400
If microalbuminuria progresses to macroalbuminuria

503
00:26:35.400 --> 00:26:38.730
that predicts progression to end stage renal disease,

504
00:26:38.730 --> 00:26:42.873
as well as diabetic retinopathy and diabetic neuropathy.

505
00:26:43.830 --> 00:26:46.437
So screen your diabetics for micro

506
00:26:46.437 --> 00:26:50.670
and macroalbuminuria at least annually.

507
00:26:50.670 --> 00:26:53.910
Type two diabetics with initial diagnosis.

508
00:26:53.910 --> 00:26:57.330
Type ones you can wait a couple years if you want.

509
00:26:57.330 --> 00:27:00.873
Abnormal values are reconfirmed and followed closely.

510
00:27:02.190 --> 00:27:06.210
So remember those numbers again, less than 30, normal.

511
00:27:06.210 --> 00:27:10.983
30 to 300 microalbuminuria, over 300 macroalbuminuria.

512
00:27:12.510 --> 00:27:16.590
How do you delay this progression to kidney disease?

513
00:27:16.590 --> 00:27:19.200
Intensive blood glucose management,

514
00:27:19.200 --> 00:27:21.450
intensive blood pressure control.

515
00:27:21.450 --> 00:27:24.780
ACEs and ARB are first line here.

516
00:27:24.780 --> 00:27:28.710
Their effect is independent of their blood pressure effect.

517
00:27:28.710 --> 00:27:32.700
The SGLT2 inhibitors also help

518
00:27:32.700 --> 00:27:35.820
to reduce end stage renal disease and mortality.

519
00:27:35.820 --> 00:27:36.870
So we use those

520
00:27:36.870 --> 00:27:38.970
and should be using those frequently

521
00:27:38.970 --> 00:27:41.283
in our diabetic patients with CKD.

522
00:27:42.480 --> 00:27:47.480
So use ACEs or ARBs in normotensive patients with diabetes

523
00:27:49.200 --> 00:27:53.310
and albumin ratios of microalbumin over 30

524
00:27:53.310 --> 00:27:54.453
who are at high risk.

525
00:27:55.290 --> 00:27:59.490
But no matter what your insurance company says,

526
00:27:59.490 --> 00:28:04.490
there's no need to use ACEs or ARBs to prevent CKD

527
00:28:04.581 --> 00:28:07.710
in patients with normal blood pressure

528
00:28:07.710 --> 00:28:09.303
and normal renal function.

529
00:28:10.800 --> 00:28:13.980
Normal blood pressure, normal renal function,

530
00:28:13.980 --> 00:28:16.680
not secreting albumin,

531
00:28:16.680 --> 00:28:18.423
they don't need ACEs or ARBs.

532
00:28:21.090 --> 00:28:24.720
You should use an SGLT2 in patient with diabetes

533
00:28:24.720 --> 00:28:28.980
and chronic kidney disease as long as the GFR is over 30

534
00:28:28.980 --> 00:28:32.700
and probably safe with the GFR over 20.

535
00:28:32.700 --> 00:28:36.000
So again, who gets ACEs and ARBs?

536
00:28:36.000 --> 00:28:39.540
Diabetics with albuminuria,

537
00:28:39.540 --> 00:28:42.900
diabetics with a GFR of less than 60,

538
00:28:42.900 --> 00:28:44.560
diabetics with hypertension

539
00:28:45.720 --> 00:28:50.720
or non-diabetics with albuminuria over 300,

540
00:28:50.760 --> 00:28:52.893
hypertension, and CKD.

541
00:28:55.440 --> 00:28:58.590
SGLT2 agents were both in diabetic

542
00:28:58.590 --> 00:29:00.840
and non-diabetic CKD.

543
00:29:00.840 --> 00:29:03.810
They reduced the decline in GFR,

544
00:29:03.810 --> 00:29:07.260
reduce the likelihood of getting CKD-5,

545
00:29:07.260 --> 00:29:09.648
mortality for cardiovascular disease,

546
00:29:09.648 --> 00:29:12.690
and hospitalizations for heart failure.

547
00:29:12.690 --> 00:29:15.807
So use them in patients with diabetic kidney disease

548
00:29:15.807 --> 00:29:19.410
and GFR over 30, perhaps over 20,

549
00:29:19.410 --> 00:29:22.083
and any of these agents here will work.

550
00:29:23.160 --> 00:29:25.534
What about finerenone?

551
00:29:25.534 --> 00:29:26.700
Known it's a nonsteroidal

552
00:29:26.700 --> 00:29:29.580
mineralocorticoid receptor agonist,

553
00:29:29.580 --> 00:29:34.320
very similar in its effectiveness as your SGLT2 agents.

554
00:29:34.320 --> 00:29:37.680
So use them in patients at increased risk

555
00:29:37.680 --> 00:29:42.030
for CKD progression who have diabetes and CKD

556
00:29:42.030 --> 00:29:46.470
who can't use ACEs or ARBs or SGLT2s,

557
00:29:46.470 --> 00:29:48.120
or get worse with renal function

558
00:29:48.120 --> 00:29:51.060
despite the use of those agents

559
00:29:51.060 --> 00:29:53.520
as long as GFR is over 25

560
00:29:53.520 --> 00:29:55.270
and they have albumin in the urine.

561
00:29:57.450 --> 00:30:01.860
Nutritional guidelines, reduce dietary protein intake.

562
00:30:01.860 --> 00:30:05.280
That may help improve renal function and is recommended.

563
00:30:05.280 --> 00:30:07.530
And again, sodium restriction too

564
00:30:07.530 --> 00:30:10.110
if you can manage it with your patient.

565
00:30:10.110 --> 00:30:11.403
Immunizations.

566
00:30:12.990 --> 00:30:17.400
Immunize patients with CKD-4 or 5 with flu annually

567
00:30:17.400 --> 00:30:21.990
with pneumococcal vaccine, against Hep B, against COVID,

568
00:30:21.990 --> 00:30:24.033
and make sure their TDaP is up to date.

569
00:30:25.050 --> 00:30:27.963
And this I think is our last question for you, I believe.

570
00:30:28.950 --> 00:30:31.080
Indications for nephrology referral

571
00:30:31.080 --> 00:30:34.050
in patient with CKD include which of the following?

572
00:30:34.050 --> 00:30:36.840
A GFR less than 30.

573
00:30:36.840 --> 00:30:40.140
A blood pressure over 130/80 despite treatment

574
00:30:40.140 --> 00:30:42.150
with an ACE and a diuretic.

575
00:30:42.150 --> 00:30:44.190
The presence of a new recently trained,

576
00:30:44.190 --> 00:30:46.983
highly indebted nephrologist in town.

577
00:30:47.850 --> 00:30:49.500
Or diabetes and a urine

578
00:30:49.500 --> 00:30:52.353
microalbumin creatinine ratio of 30 to 300.

579
00:30:57.990 --> 00:30:59.640
It's that first one.

580
00:30:59.640 --> 00:31:02.490
The one who's now at stage four CKD.

581
00:31:02.490 --> 00:31:05.040
If they haven't seen 'em already, they should.

582
00:31:05.040 --> 00:31:07.680
So referrals for acute complex

583
00:31:07.680 --> 00:31:12.120
or severe cardiovascular disease with CKD

584
00:31:12.120 --> 00:31:17.010
anemia, bone and mineral disorders that you can't manage,

585
00:31:17.010 --> 00:31:18.840
adverse medication effects,

586
00:31:18.840 --> 00:31:21.480
severe hyperkalemia despite treatment,

587
00:31:21.480 --> 00:31:24.810
refractory proteinuria, resistant hypertension

588
00:31:24.810 --> 00:31:27.990
that's not responsive with at least three good drugs,

589
00:31:27.990 --> 00:31:29.910
stage four CKD,

590
00:31:29.910 --> 00:31:33.060
or an unexplained decreased in GFR over 30%

591
00:31:33.060 --> 00:31:36.033
over four months and you're not able to figure out why.

592
00:31:37.200 --> 00:31:40.200
Evidence-based guidelines are to use an ACE inhibitor

593
00:31:40.200 --> 00:31:42.750
or an ARB, as we mentioned earlier.

594
00:31:42.750 --> 00:31:44.790
Don't use 'em together.

595
00:31:44.790 --> 00:31:47.910
Remember the hemoglobin goal should not be over 11

596
00:31:47.910 --> 00:31:49.503
if you're gonna use EPO.

597
00:31:51.330 --> 00:31:53.280
Here are your answers.

598
00:31:53.280 --> 00:31:58.280
So congratulations on making it through AKI and CKD.

599
00:31:58.801 --> 00:32:01.634
(dramatic music)

